{
  "doc_id": "9622",
  "text": "Several parameters can influence the thermal radiative properties (reflectance, transmittance, absorptance and emittance) [CITATION_1] of these compounds such as the intrinsic ones, namely the structural state of the bulk parts (crystalline or amorphous) [CITATION_2] , and the extrinsic ones, namely their textures [CITATION_3] , and of course their thicknesses when they are shaped as a slab. From a radiative viewpoint, the term texture stands here for the spatial arrangement of the optical heterogeneities [CITATION_4] such as the gaseous pores embedded in the carbon-based host matrix and their respective size distributions [CITATION_5] . Let us remark that according to the thermal history undergone by the sample and to its texture anisotropy different radiative behaviours can be reached [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Moreover, the intrinsic radiative properties are also governed by the ratio of sp [CITATION_8] (graphitelike) to sp [CITATION_9] (diamondlike) chemical bonds [CITATION_10] .",
